<ContentLayout title="Supply and Demand" description="Why the grid must balance supply and demand every second, and what happens when it cannot.">

<h1>Supply and Demand</h1>

<p class="text-xl" style="color: var(--color-text-muted); max-width: 600px;">
  The grid has no warehouse. Electricity must be generated the instant it is consumed.
  Balancing supply and demand across an entire continent is the hardest real-time control
  problem on Earth.
</p>

<div class="my-6" style="height: 1px; background: linear-gradient(to right, transparent, var(--color-surface-light), transparent);"></div>

<!-- ── Briefing: Why Balance Matters ── -->

<h2 id="why-balance-matters">Why Balance Matters</h2>

<p>
  Every appliance you turn on draws power from the grid. Every generator feeding the grid
  must collectively produce exactly as much power as all consumers are drawing -- not a
  megawatt more, not a megawatt less.
</p>

<p>
  When supply exceeds demand, frequency rises above 50 Hz. When demand exceeds supply,
  frequency drops. Small deviations are normal. But if frequency strays too far, generators
  disconnect to protect themselves, loads trip offline, and the grid can cascade into
  blackout.
</p>

<h2 id="demand-never-stops">Demand Never Stops</h2>

<p>
  Demand follows predictable daily patterns: low at night when most people sleep,
  rising in the morning as industry and offices come online, dipping midday, then
  peaking in the evening when everyone comes home, cooks, and turns on lights and
  heating. But predictable does not mean easy -- the operator must have enough
  generation ready for every moment of the day.
</p>

<p>
  On top of the daily pattern, demand shifts with weather (heatwaves push air conditioning,
  cold snaps drive electric heating), holidays, major TV events, and industrial schedules.
  The grid operator must forecast all of this and dispatch generators accordingly.
</p>

<h2 id="the-balancing-act">The Balancing Act</h2>

<p>
  Grid operators use a portfolio of generation assets, each with different response
  characteristics:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Baseload</strong> -- large coal or nuclear plants that run continuously. Cheap per MWh but slow to adjust.</li>
  <li><strong>Mid-merit</strong> -- gas turbines that can ramp up or down over minutes. More expensive but flexible.</li>
  <li><strong>Peakers</strong> -- fast-start gas or diesel generators kept on standby for demand spikes. Expensive, but can respond in seconds.</li>
  <li><strong>Batteries</strong> -- instant response, but limited by stored energy. Ideal for short bursts.</li>
  <li><strong>Renewables</strong> -- solar and wind are cheap but variable. The operator cannot control the weather.</li>
</ul>

<p>
  The art of grid operation is dispatching these assets so that total supply tracks total
  demand, keeping frequency within the safe band of 49.8--50.2 Hz.
</p>

