<!-- ── Briefing: Storage at Scale ── -->

<h2 id="why-storage-matters">Why Storage Matters</h2>

<p>
  If batteries are so fast and flexible, why not just build enough to buffer the entire
  grid? The answer is scale. Europe draws roughly 300 GW of power on average. The
  world's largest lithium-ion battery installation -- Moss Landing in California --
  stores just 3 GWh. That is enough to power Europe for about 36 seconds.
</p>

<p>
  Even pumped hydro, which accounts for over 90% of all grid-scale energy storage on
  Earth, totals only about 9,000 GWh globally. That would cover roughly 30 hours of
  European demand. Building enough centralised storage to fully buffer a continental
  grid is simply not feasible with current technology.
</p>

<!-- ── Lab: Storage Scale Visualizer ── -->

<h2 id="storage-scale">Explore: Storage Scale</h2>

<p>
  Stack up Moss Landing batteries and see how long they would power the European grid.
  Compare with all the pumped hydro storage on Earth. The numbers reveal why
  distributed coordination -- virtual power plants -- is the path forward.
</p>

<div class="my-8 scroll-mt-20">
  <StorageScaleVisualizer client:visible />
</div>

<!-- ── Closing ── -->

<h2 id="what-comes-next">What Comes Next</h2>

<p>
  The grid cannot store its way out of the balancing problem with giant batteries alone.
  But what if millions of small batteries -- in homes, electric vehicles, and commercial
  buildings -- could be coordinated to act as one? That is the idea behind a
  <strong>virtual power plant</strong>.
</p>

